I don't think very highly about people who don't know what the @#%$ they're talking about and then insult me for their mistakes and/or assumptions.<br>
<br>
When did I say it was a good thing not to be scared by scary movies? I just said I didn't find the movie scary. I LIKED the movie, and I like many other movies, whether or not they scare me. You watch &quot;scary&quot; movies to be scared? Good for you. I'm NOT you. Just because I watch movies for a different reason, that doesn't make me wrong. Also, when did I ever say that just because I'm not scared that I cosidered them stupid? <br>
<br>
And the biggest mistake of your whole post is this idiotic &quot;scary&quot; movie crap. A &quot;scary&quot; movie? I believe that would be quite a subjective way of categorizing a movie. I like HORROR movies... I believe that would be the actual term for these movies. In fact, that is one of my favorite genres. I don't appreciate your assuming that everyone should watch them for the same reasons you do. Whether I derive my entertainment from being scared or anything else from watching one is my own damn business, and just because my reason for enjoying them is different from yours doesn't make me or anyone else wrong for doing so. <br>
<br>
And that idiocy about people not being scared because they don't &quot;get it&quot; is pathetic. Even if that were true, that's the fault of the movie for not conveying that feeling properly. And last time I checked, being frightened wasn't some especially cerebral activity. It's not like after contemplating the deeper meaning of The Shining that all of a sudden you'll break out into cold sweats and get freaked out.<br>
<br>
Now get off your high horse and recognize that people don't necessarily have to like things for the same reason as you. <p><html>
